{{for|the broader political and theological tradition|Christian socialism}} {{Social Christianity}}
'''Christians for Socialism''' ({{lang-es|'''Cristianos por el socialismo'''}}; '''CPS''') was a worldwide political and cultural movement focused on [[social inequality]] and economic injustice,<ref name="Onis 1972"/> inspired by [[liberation theology]].{{sfnm |1a1=B.&nbsp;H. Smith |1y=1982 |1p=232 |2a1=Turner |2y=1994 |2p=8}} It was founded in 1971.
==Founding== Having begun in April 1971,{{sfn|Lies|Malone|2006|p=91}} Christians for Socialism first gained notoriety when a collection of eighty [[Chile]]an priests, known as the "Group of 80", publicly declared their support of the construction of [[socialism]] along the lines being followed by then-President [[Salvador Allende]].<ref name="Onis 1972"/>{{sfn|Nessan|2012|p=41}} The Secretariat of Christians for Socialism was formally established in September 1973. The group was predominantly composed of [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] members of the [[Christian left]] who were inspired and spurred on by the [[Second Vatican Council]].
==Project== CPS was founded to counteract a presumption that Christian institutions were inherently opposed to [[socialism]]. While its founders found aspects of socialist programs that they wished to critique, they wanted to do so as insiders within the socialist movement, rather than as adversaries.{{sfn|C. Smith|1991|p=182}} From their beginnings as supporters of Allende,{{sfn|Eecmy|n.d.|p=116}} CPS has been associated with firm support for socialist leaders.{{sfn|Floridi|1986|p=49}} Accordingly, CPS leaders cultivated strong ties with Cuban Marxist politician [[Fidel Castro]].{{sfnm |1a1=Floridi |1y=1986 |1p=49 |2a1=C. Smith |2y=1991 |2pp=182ff}} It was intended as a movement of active political involvement and participation,{{sfn|C. Smith|1991|pp=182ff}} and involved discussions bringing together current political events and church documents in light of each other.{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=8}} CPS inspired a series of social programs in the public sector.<!--{{citation-needed}}--> Priests in CPS led union units and organized peasant federations.<ref name="Onis 1972"/>
==Antecedents== <!-- For more detail, see B. H. Smith 1982:249 --> In Chile the immediate antecedent to CPS was the ''{{ill|Iglesia Joven|es}}'' movement.{{sfnm |1a1=Garcés |1y=2011 |1p=222 |2a1=Hojman |2y=1985 |2p=72}}<!--<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Commonweal|date=1975|volume=102|page=269|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zzkdAQAAMAAJ&dq=%22Iglesia+Joven%22+%22Christians+for+Socialism%22|accessdate=31 January 2017}}</ref>--> In Italy, many of the young people who had been involved in the [[1968 movement in Italy|Italian student and worker protests of 1968]] joined the movement, and the [[Christian Associations of Italian Workers]] (ACLI) was very supportive.
==Leaders== [[Alfonso López Trujillo|López Trujillo]] considers {{ill|Giulio Girardi|es||it}} a major leader of CPS.{{sfn|McGovern|1989|p=48}} Another prominent leader was the [[Salesians of Don Bosco|Salesian]] priest {{ill|Lidia Menapace|de||it}}, who was also a significant figure in the [[Italian resistance movement|Italian Catholic resistance during World War II]]. In Spain, [[Alfonso Carlos Comín]] was a key leader in establishing the movement. The theologian [[Gustavo Gutiérrez]] was also a member{{sfn|Bell|2001|p=80}} and led sessions at all the major conferences.{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=8}}
==Suppression== CPS faced opposition from the start. [[Left-wing politics|Left-leaning]] priests from Brazil and Bolivia were supportive but unable to participate in gatherings due to severe police control.<ref name="Onis 1972"/> CPS was short-lived in Chile, due to strong resistance from the [[Episcopal Conference of Chile]] under the direction of its secretary general, bishop [[Carlos Oviedo Cavada]].{{sfnm |1a1=Marshner |1y=1974 |1p=42 |2a1=Tombs |2y=2002 |2p=148}} In their letter condemning the movement, the bishops there argued that while the church speaks to "politics insofar as it underlies every social reality", it should not be involved in "partisan activity".{{sfn|Eagleson|1975|pp=196f}} Chilean clergy involved in the movement were banned from political participation altogether in April 1973.{{sfnm |1a1=Cavada |1y=1974 |2a1=Lies |2a2=Malone |2y=2006 |2p=92}} The movement was suppressed by the Chilean military government after the [[1973 Chilean coup d'état|coup of 1973]].{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=8}} Father {{ill|Pablo Richard|de|Pablo Richard|es|Pablo Richard Guzmán|pt|Pablo Richard}}, one of the most active members of CPS, left Chile at this time.{{sfn|Sigmund|1990|p=229}}
==Gatherings== A number of important gatherings have been held under the auspices of Christians for Socialism. In 1972, 400 members met for a week at a textile union hall, urging "class struggle [as] the only valid course to necessary social change in Latin America."<ref name="Onis 1972">{{cite news | last=De Onis | first=Juan | title=Assembly in Chile Urges Socialism | newspaper=The New York Times | date=4 May 1972 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/05/04/archives/assembly-in-chile-urges-socialism-group-led-by-priests-seeks.html | accessdate=10 December 2016}}</ref> CPS brought together similar Latin American movements in the Latin American Meeting of Christians for Socialism 1974 in [[Santiago]], Chile.
In 1975, the Christians for Socialism conference in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], formally introduced [[liberation theology]] to the United States.{{sfn|Turner|1994|p=8}} This event was a significant convergence where [[Black theology|black]], [[feminism|feminist]], and third-world [[Anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]] movements joined together and recognized each other as peers in the same process of liberation, while also strongly critiquing one another.{{sfn|Turner|1994|pp=8f}} A detailed account of the meeting was published.{{sfn|Torres|Eagleson|1976}}
Christians for Socialism groups sprung up in France, Italy, and West Germany.{{sfn|May|2003|p=101}} In Germany, CPS was a radical rival to [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] liberalism and "[[German idealism]]'s aspirations to freedom".{{sfn|May|2003|p=101}}
==Present day== The CPS group has as fundamental milestone the celebration of its annual conferences that are held in Spain, alternately in [[Madrid]] and [[Barcelona]]. CPS has a presence mainly in Madrid, Catalonia, Menorca and with individuals in different autonomous communities, such as Andalusia, Galicia, Aragon and others. At present, the CPS group remains within a larger movement called "Christian Networks", as a critical and reflective encounter in relation to the church, society, and politics.
In the United States, Christians for Socialism was most active through the 1970s and early 1980s. After the election of [[Ronald Reagan]], the movement lost some of its momentum and disbanded. However, in January 2018, Christians for Socialism: North America restarted its struggle for a Christian left organized around the same ideas from the movement started in Chile in 1972.<ref>{{cite web |date=15 January 2018 |title=Manifesto |url=https://christiansforsocialism.org/manifesto/ |publisher=Christians for Socialism |access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>
==Critiques== López Trujillo has critiqued CPS for holding an understanding of liberation too strongly influenced by [[Marxism|Marxist]] political theory rather than the integral Christian liberation stance espoused by the [[Latin American Episcopal Conference]].{{sfn|McGovern|1989|p=48}} It has been said{{by whom|date=August 2017}} that for some members of Christians for Socialism, there is "no salvation incarnate outside of class struggle."{{sfn|Ortiz|1980|p=102}}
