{{Infobox ancient site |name = Tell Sukas |native_name = |alternate_name = Shuksi, Suksi |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Syria |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location =near [[Jableh]], [[Syria]] |region = [[Canaan]] |coordinates = {{coord|35.306318|35.922203|display=inline}} |type = [[Tell (archaeology)|Tell]] |part_of = Town |length = |width = |area ={{convert|1.9|ha|ft2}} |height = |builder = |material = Clay, Limestone |built = |abandoned = c. 69 BC |epochs = [[Late Bronze Age]], [[Iron Age]] |cultures = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = 1958–1963 |archaeologists =[[P.J. Riis]] |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = [[Directorate-General of Antiquities and Museums]] |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} '''Tell Sukas''' (ancient '''Shuksi''' or '''Suksi''') is a [[Late Bronze Age]] [[Tell (archaeology)|archaeological mound]] on the [[Eastern Mediterranean]] coast about {{convert|6|km|mi}} south of [[Jableh]], [[Syria]].
==Overview== Tell Sukas was located at the center of the fertile plain of Jableh on a hill with access to two natural harbors.<ref name="Aubet">Aubet, 2001, p. 63</ref> There is evidence of an earlier [[Neolithic]] settlement at the site dating back to the seventh or sixth millennium BC.<ref name="Tobias">Fischer-Hansen, 1991, p. 44</ref> The site was identified as ancient Suksi, which was mentioned in the [[Ugarit]] tablets and was probably the southernmost port of the Kingdom of Ugarit.<ref name="Bromiley">Bromiley, 1995, p. 272</ref> The [[Bronze Age]] settlement was probably destroyed along with the capital, Ugarit, during the [[Bronze Age collapse]].<ref>[[Robert Drews|Drews]], 1995, p. 14</ref> The site was reused shortly thereafter and commercial activity at the [[Iron Age]] settlement can be traced again to at least the tenth century BC,<ref name="Aubet"/> when it became the port of [[Luhuti]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNvovfA4o_4C&pg=PA133#v=onepage&q&f=false|title= Crafts and Images in Contact: Studies on Eastern Mediterranean Art of the First Millennium BCE|author= Claudia E. Suter, Christoph Uehlinger|page= 133}}</ref> A [[Phoenicians|Phoenician]] settlement was established in the eighth century BC<ref>Horden; Purcell, 2000, p. 404</ref> and the town thrived as a [[Ancient Greeks|Greek]] trading outpost between c. 850 BC and c. 550 BC, when it was destroyed by the [[Babylonians]].<ref name="Bromiley"/><ref>Tuplin, 1996, p. 36</ref> Recent excavations reveal that the site was inhabited again by the Phoenicians between 380 and 69 BC until it was destroyed again, possibly by an earthquake. It was later re-occupied for a short period by the [[Crusaders]].<ref name="Tobias"/>
==Excavation== The site was excavated in 1958–1963 by the Danish Carlsberg Expedition to Phoenicia under [[P.J. Riis]]. Excavations uncovered an early Iron Age cemetery south of the tell which was dated to between the 13th and 10th century BC. Excavations also uncovered a large seventh-century Phoenician temple. The abundance of Greek pottery and the discovery of Greek burial grounds suggest that the city became a permanent Hellenic outpost by 600 BC.<ref name="Aubet"/>
